      margin-top: 6px;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <h1>BTC Cycle Real Account Tracking System</h1>

  <p><strong>Document purpose:</strong> This is the plain-language operating manual for tracking the Bitcoin four-year-cycle system studied in the BTC_cyc workbook. It is designed for real-account monitoring, daily review, and a future GitHub dashboard.</p>

  <p><strong>Primary system:</strong> Bitcoin four-year-cycle timing using the halving date and cycle day count.</p>

  <div class="rule">
    Trading rule: hold BTC from the halving day through cycle day 540. Hold cash outside that window.
  </div>

  <h2>1. Strategy Summary</h2>

  <table>
    <tr>
      <th>Item</th>
      <th>Rule</th>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Invested asset</td>
      <td>BTC, represented by BTC-USD or a real Bitcoin holding.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Defensive asset</td>
      <td>Cash or Treasury-like cash equivalent. The backtest treats this as cash with no interest.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Signal source</td>
      <td>Bitcoin halving date and the number of days since that halving.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Buy / hold window</td>
      <td>Cycle day 0 through cycle day 540, inclusive.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Sell / cash window</td>
      <td>Cycle day 541 until the next halving day.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Current 2024-cycle anchor</td>
      <td>Halving date: April 20, 2024. Day 540: October 12, 2025.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Current status as of June 27, 2026</td>
      <td>Cycle day 798, which is outside the tested BTC holding window. The model status is Hold Cash.</td>
    </tr>
  </table>

  <h2>2. Exact Operating Rules</h2>

  <h3>Entry Rule</h3>
  <p>Enter or hold BTC on the halving day and continue holding through cycle day 540. For the 2024 cycle, that holding window ran from April 20, 2024 through October 12, 2025.</p>

  <h3>Exit Rule</h3>
  <p>Exit BTC after cycle day 540 and move the strategy sleeve to cash. For the 2024 cycle, the first cash day after the tested holding window was October 13, 2025.</p>

  <h3>Re-entry Rule</h3>
  <p>Remain in cash until the next confirmed Bitcoin halving date. On the next halving date, the new cycle day becomes 0 and the system re-enters BTC.</p>

  <h3>No Override Indicators</h3>
  <p>The 200-week moving average was studied, but it is not the primary real-account trigger for this system. The best tested BTC-only rule in the workbook was the halving-cycle day 0-540 rule, not the 200-week-SMA rule.</p>

  <h2>3. Current-Cycle Calendar</h2>

  <table>
    <tr>
      <th>Milestone</th>
      <th>Date</th>
      <th>Meaning</th>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>2024 halving</td>
      <td>April 20, 2024</td>
      <td>Cycle day 0. Model enters or holds BTC.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Day 540</td>
      <td>October 12, 2025</td>
      <td>Last day of the tested BTC holding window.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>First cash day</td>
      <td>October 13, 2025</td>
      <td>Model exits BTC and holds cash.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Estimated bottom window from prior study</td>
      <td>Early to late October 2026</td>
      <td>Useful for planning gradual accumulation, but this is not a formal signal in the tested rule.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Next halving</td>
      <td>To be confirmed by network block height</td>
      <td>The next formal re-entry point for the tested BTC cycle system.</td>
    </tr>
  </table>

  <h2>4. Backtest Results Used For This Manual</h2>

  <p>The core BTC-only comparison came from <strong>Bitcoin_strategy_comparison.csv</strong> and <strong>Bitcoin_4YearCycle_vs_200WeekSMA.xlsx</strong>.</p>

  <table>
    <tr>
      <th>Strategy</th>
      <th>Test Window</th>
      <th>Final Value From $1,000</th>
      <th>CAGR</th>
