  <h2>5. Account Tracking Checklist</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Record the latest BTC price and date.</li>
    <li>Confirm the most recent halving date used by the tracker.</li>
    <li>Calculate the cycle day: latest date minus halving date, with halving day as day 0.</li>
    <li>If cycle day is 0 through 540, account status is Hold BTC.</li>
    <li>If cycle day is 541 or later, account status is Hold Cash.</li>
    <li>Keep the formal signal separate from discretionary DCA planning.</li>
    <li>When the next halving occurs, update the halving date and reset cycle day to 0.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>6. Dashboard Fields To Track</h2>

  <table>
    <tr>
      <th>Field</th>
      <th>Purpose</th>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Current status</td>
      <td>Hold BTC or Hold Cash.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>BTC close</td>
      <td>Latest BTC-USD adjusted close or reference price.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Market date</td>
      <td>Date of the latest price used.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Halving date</td>
      <td>The active cycle anchor.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Cycle day</td>
      <td>Days since the active halving date.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Days to / from day 540</td>
      <td>Shows whether the model is before, inside, or after the formal BTC holding window.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>200-week SMA</td>
      <td>Context only, not the active trigger.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Realized price</td>
      <td>On-chain cost-basis context. Compute from CoinMetrics as BTC price divided by MVRV when <strong>CapMVRVCur</strong> is available. This is not the active trigger.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Estimated electrical cost per BTC</td>
      <td>Mining cost context. Compute from network hash rate, assumed miner efficiency, assumed electricity price, and daily BTC issuance. This is a model estimate, not a single official value.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Recent signal history</td>
      <td>Recent daily rows showing date, price, cycle day, and status.</td>
    </tr>
  </table>

  <h2>7. On-Chain And Mining-Cost Context</h2>

  <p>These indicators can help describe whether BTC is near historically important cost-basis or miner-cost zones, but they do not override the primary cycle rule.</p>

  <table>
    <tr>
      <th>Indicator</th>
      <th>How To Calculate</th>
      <th>Latest Local Example</th>
      <th>Dashboard Label</th>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Realized price</td>
      <td>CoinMetrics ReferenceRateUSD divided by CapMVRVCur.</td>
      <td>Using the latest complete local CoinMetrics row, May 23, 2026: ReferenceRateUSD $75,567.54 / MVRV 1.4146 = about $53,421.</td>
      <td>On-chain cost basis, context only.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Estimated electrical cost per BTC</td>
      <td>HashRate TH/s x miner efficiency J/TH x 86,400 / 3,600,000 = kWh/day. Then multiply by electricity price and divide by BTC issued that day.</td>
      <td>Using May 23, 2026 local CoinMetrics hash rate, 30 J/TH, $0.05/kWh, and 512.5 BTC issued: about $78,230 per BTC.</td>
      <td>Estimated mining electrical cost, context only.</td>
    </tr>
  </table>

  <div class="note">
    Electrical cost is assumption-sensitive. A lower power price or more efficient miner lowers the estimate; a higher power price or older equipment raises it. The dashboard should display the assumptions next to the number.
  </div>

  <h2>8. Important Guardrails</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>This manual is for tracking a rules-based study. It is not financial advice.</li>
    <li>Do not treat the October 2026 bottom-window estimate as an automatic buy signal. It is a planning estimate, not the tested rule.</li>
    <li>Do not treat realized price or estimated electrical cost as automatic buy signals. They are bottom-status context indicators only.</li>
    <li>Do not replace the BTC cycle rule with QQQ, QLD, SPY, SSO, TQQQ, MACD, or moving-average rules in this account tracker.</li>
    <li>For real money, verify the data source, tax impact, trading vehicle, custody risk, and cash vehicle before acting.</li>
    <li>When updating the dashboard, use real BTC data and make the data date visible.</li>
  </ul>

